File: Nkosi Johnson, an AIDS sufferer, poses with his foster mother Gayle Johnson (L) at their home in Johannesburg 28 November 2000. JOHANNESBURG -  Google honoured South African child Aids activist Nkosi Johnson with his very own Google Doodle on Tuesday in celebration of what would have been his 31st birthday. Johnson is remembered as the child who impacted many by pushing the boundaries of public perceptions of HIV/Aids. READ: Google doodle dedicated to SA elections He was 12 when he died in 2001, and at the time was also the longest-surviving child born HIV-positive. His memory lives on through his mother, Gail Johnson, who runs Nkosi's Haven. Google doodle in honour of late HIV/AIDS activist Nkosi Johnson.